{"title_page": "Vanidasan", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date = April 2020}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name = Vanidasan\n| image = Vanidasan.jpg\n| image_size = 180px\n| caption = \n| native_name = \u0bb5\u0bbe\u0ba3\u0bbf\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0b9a\u0ba9\u0bcd\n| native_name_lang = ta\n| pseudonym = Rami\n| birth_name = Arangasamy Ethirasalu\n| birth_date = 22 July 1915\n| birth_place = [[Villianur]], [[Puducherry]], India\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1974|8|7|1915|7|22}}\n| spouse = Adilakshmi\n| occupation = Teacher, [[Poet|Tamil poet]]\n| parents = Father : Thirukkumu<br>Mother : Tulsiammal\n| honorific_prefix = Paavendar\n}}\n'''Vanidasan''' (July 22, 1915 - August 7, 1974) was a 20th-century Tamil poet and poet. He was known to be one from Pavalar generation known as [[Bharathidasan|'Bharathidasan's]] ancestry'. He was an expert in Tamil, Telugu, English and French.<ref name=\"eluthu\">{{Cite web|url=https://eluthu.com/poetprofile/Vanidasan-|title=\u0bb5\u0bbe\u0ba3\u0bbf\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0b9a\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bc1\u0bb1\u0bbf\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1 Vanidasan|language=ta|website=Eluthu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> He had published over 17 collections of poetry, including several novels in poetry form.<ref name=\"TheHindu\">{{Cite news|last=Kishore|first=Kavita|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/puducherry/book-on-revolutionary-poet-vanidasan-released-in-puducherry/article5772927.ece|title=Book on revolutionary poet Vanidasan released in Puducherry|date=2014-03-11|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-08|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nHe was born in [[Villianur]], next to [[Puducherry]], for father Thirukkumu and mother Tulsiammal. His parents named him as Arangasamy. His was also known by his nickname 'Rami'.<ref name=\"Dinamani\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dinamani.com/specials/kalvimani/2013/dec/29/\u0ba4\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0bcd-\u0b85\u0bb1\u0bbf\u0b9e\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd-\u0b85\u0bb1\u0bbf\u0bb5\u0bcb\u0bae\u0bcd-\u0b95\u0bb5-810945.html|title=\u0ba4\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0bcd \u0b85\u0bb1\u0bbf\u0b9e\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd \u0b85\u0bb1\u0bbf\u0bb5\u0bcb\u0bae\u0bcd: \u0b95\u0bb5\u0bbf\u0b9e\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0bb5\u0bbe\u0ba3\u0bbf\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0b9a\u0ba9\u0bcd|website=Dinamani|language=ta|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nHe was taught primary education by writer [[Bharathidasan]]. He started writing under the pen name \u2018Ra-Mi\u2019.<ref name=\"TheHindu\" /> He published his songs in the book ''Tamil Kavithai Kalanjiyam'' published by [[Sahitya Akademi]] and in a book published by the Southern Language Book Publishing Publishing Group. His songs have been translated into [[Russian language|Russian]] and [[English language|English]].<ref name=\"eluthu\" /> He was also proficient in [[French language|French]], in which he had published ''Tamil-French Kaiagara Mudali''.\n\nIn 1935, Vanidasan married Adilakshmi, daughter of his younger brother. They had nine children, male and female. The eldest of them was Madhuri and V Kaliyamoorthy who were married on 10.5.1959 under the leadership of Mayilai Sivamuthu.<ref name=\"one\">''Thennagam'', 8-5-1959; Chennai; P .6</ref>\n\n== Honours ==\nHe was complimented as 'Wordsworth of Tamil Nadu' as his songs excelled in portraying nature. He received the [[Legion of Honour|Chevalier honour]] from the French president.<ref name=\"TheHindu\" /><ref name=\"eluthu\" /> Titles such as 'Pavalar Mani', 'Paavendar' were also given to Vanidasan. He worked as a Tamil teacher for 34 years of his life.<ref name=\"eluthu\" /> He was also praised by scholar [[Thiru. V. Kalyanasundaram]] for his works. Mayilai Sivamuthu lauded him as the 'Tagore of Tamil Nadu'<ref name=\"madhumathi\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.madhumathi.com/2013/07/blog-post_2657.html|title=\u0ba4\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0b95\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0bb5\u0bc7\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0bb8\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bcd \u0bb5\u0bbe\u0ba3\u0bbf\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0b9a\u0ba9\u0bcd|language=ta|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nVanidasan died on 7 August 1974. His family was given a gift of {{INRConvert|10000|year=1974}} in appreciation by the [[Government of Tamil Nadu|Tamil Nadu government]]. A government high school in [[Seliamedu]] was named after him. The Tamil Nadu government has also [[nationalised]] his works.<ref name=\"madhumathi\" />\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin|2}}\n#''Iravu Varavillai''\n#''Inba Ilakiyam''\n#''Inikum Paatu''\n#''Ezhil Virutham''\n#''Ezhiloviyam''\n#''Kulanthai Ilakiyam''\n#''Kodi Mullai''\n#''Siritha Nuna''\n#''Tamizhachi''\n#''Theertha Yathirai''\n#''Thoduvaanam''\n#''Paataranga Padalgal''\n#''Paatu Pirakumadaa''\n#''Periya Edathu Seithi''\n#''Pokarparisu''\n#''Vanidasan Poems \u2014 First Vol''\n#''Vanidasan Poetry \u2014 Second Vol''\n#''Vanidasan Poetry \u2014 Third Vol''\n{{refend}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.tamilvu.org/ta/library-nationalized-html-naauthor-83-235740 Works by Vanidasan \u2014 Tamil Virtual Academy (in Tamil)]\n\n[[Category:1974 deaths]]\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:Indian poets]]\n[[Category:Tamil poets]]\n[[Category:Tamil writers]]\n[[Category:Poets from Puducherry]]\n[[Category:Indian Tamil people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian poets]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date = April 2020}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name = Vanidasan\n| image = Vanidasan.jpg\n| image_size = 180px\n| caption = \n| native_name = \u0bb5\u0bbe\u0ba3\u0bbf\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0b9a\u0ba9\u0bcd\n| native_name_lang = ta\n| pseudonym = Rami\n| birth_name = Arangasamy Ethirasalu\n| birth_date = 22 July 1915\n| birth_place = [[Villianur]], [[Puducherry]], India\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1974|8|7|1915|7|22}}\n| spouse = Adilakshmi\n| occupation = Teacher, [[Poet|Tamil poet]]\n| parents = Father : Thirukkumu<br>Mother : Tulsiammal\n| honorific_prefix = Paavendar\n}}\n'''Vanidasan''' (July 22, 1915 - August 7, 1974) was a 20th-century Tamil poet and poet. He was known to be one from Pavalar generation known as [[Bharathidasan|'Bharathidasan's]] ancestry'. He was an expert in Tamil, Telugu, English and French.<ref name=\"eluthu\">{{Cite web|url=https://eluthu.com/poetprofile/Vanidasan-|title=\u0bb5\u0bbe\u0ba3\u0bbf\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0b9a\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bc1\u0bb1\u0bbf\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1 Vanidasan|language=ta|website=Eluthu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> He had published over 17 collections of poetry, including several novels in poetry form.<ref name=\"TheHindu\">{{Cite news|last=Kishore|first=Kavita|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/puducherry/book-on-revolutionary-poet-vanidasan-released-in-puducherry/article5772927.ece|title=Book on revolutionary poet Vanidasan released in Puducherry|date=2014-03-11|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-08|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nHe was born in [[Villianur]], next to [[Puducherry]], for father Thirukkumu and mother Tulsiammal. His parents named him as Arangasamy. His was also known by his nickname 'Rami'.<ref name=\"Dinamani\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dinamani.com/specials/kalvimani/2013/dec/29/\u0ba4\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0bcd-\u0b85\u0bb1\u0bbf\u0b9e\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd-\u0b85\u0bb1\u0bbf\u0bb5\u0bcb\u0bae\u0bcd-\u0b95\u0bb5-810945.html|title=\u0ba4\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0bcd \u0b85\u0bb1\u0bbf\u0b9e\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd \u0b85\u0bb1\u0bbf\u0bb5\u0bcb\u0bae\u0bcd: \u0b95\u0bb5\u0bbf\u0b9e\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0bb5\u0bbe\u0ba3\u0bbf\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0b9a\u0ba9\u0bcd|website=Dinamani|language=ta|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nHe was taught primary education by writer [[Bharathidasan]]. He started writing under the pen name \u2018Ra-Mi\u2019.<ref name=\"TheHindu\" /> He published his songs in the book ''Tamil Kavithai Kalanjiyam'' published by [[Sahitya Akademi]] and in a book published by the Southern Language Book Publishing Publishing Group. His songs have been translated into [[Russian language|Russian]] and [[English language|English]].<ref name=\"eluthu\" /> He was also proficient in [[French language|French]], in which he had published ''Tamil-French Kaiagara Mudali''.\n\nIn 1935, Vanidasan married Adilakshmi, daughter of his younger brother. They had nine children, male and female. The eldest of them was Madhuri and V Kaliyamoorthy who were married on 10.5.1959 under the leadership of Mayilai Sivamuthu.<ref name=\"one\"> ''Thennagam'', 8-5-1959; Chennai; P .6</ref>\n\n== Honours ==\nHe was complimented as 'Wordsworth of Tamil Nadu' as his songs excelled in portraying nature. He received the [[Legion of Honour|Chevalier honour]] from the French president.<ref name=\"TheHindu\" /><ref name=\"eluthu\" /> Titles such as 'Pavalar Mani', 'Paavendar' were also given to Vanidasan. He worked as a Tamil teacher for 34 years of his life.<ref name=\"eluthu\" /> He was also praised by scholar [[Thiru. V. Kalyanasundaram]] for his works. Mayilai Sivamuthu lauded him as the 'Tagore of Tamil Nadu'<ref name=\"madhumathi\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.madhumathi.com/2013/07/blog-post_2657.html|title=\u0ba4\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0b95\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0bb5\u0bc7\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0bb8\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bcd \u0bb5\u0bbe\u0ba3\u0bbf\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0b9a\u0ba9\u0bcd|language=ta|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nVanidasan died on 7 August 1974. His family was given a gift of {{INRConvert|10000|year=1974}} in appreciation by the [[Government of Tamil Nadu|Tamil Nadu government]]. A government high school in [[Seliamedu]] was named after him. The Tamil Nadu government has also [[nationalised]] his works.<ref name=\"madhumathi\" />\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin|2}}\n#''Iravu Varavillai''\n#''Inba Ilakiyam''\n#''Inikum Paatu''\n#''Ezhil Virutham''\n#''Ezhiloviyam''\