{"title_page": "Russia\u2013Transnistria relations", "text_new": "'''Russia\u2013Transnistria relations''' (Russian: \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e-\u043f\u0440\u0438\u0434\u043d\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043e\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f) is the bilateral relationship between the [[Pridnestrovian Moldovan Republic]] and the [[Russian Federation]]. Russia does not officially recognize the independence of Transnistria. Nevertheless, Russia maintains special relations with Transnistria in the political, military, cultural and economic spheres.\n\n==History==\nThe state of Transnistria was created by local economic elites with special relations to the Soviet and later Russian centre.<ref>Jan Zofka: ''Postsowjetischer Separatismus \u2013 Die pro-russl\u00e4ndischen Bewegungen im moldauischen Dnjestr-Tal und auf der Krim 1989\u20131995'', G\u00f6ttingen: Wallstein Verlag, 2015, passim.</ref>\n\nDuring the reign of [[Igor Smirnov]] (1991\u20132011) maintaining special relations with Russia was a priority of Transnistria.<ref>Marcin Kosienkowski: ''Continuity and Change in Transnistria\u2019s Foreign Policy after the 2011 Presidential Elections'', Lublin: The Catholic University of Lublin Publishing House, 2012, p. 23. [https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/Delivery.cfm/SSRN_ID2183608_code1884160.pdf?abstractid=2143330&mirid=1 Available here.]</ref>\n\nDuring a visit to Kiev in 2010, President [[Dmitri Medvedev]] said he supported a \"special status\" for Transnistria and recognised the \"important and stabilising\" role of the Russian army.<ref>[http://english.hotnews.ro/stiri-regional_europe-7287838-the-transnistrian-conflict-russia-and-ukraine-talk-about-coordinated-effort-american-analysts-consider-the-has-abandoned-the-neighbourhood-russia.htm Anne-Marie Blajan: ''The Transnistrian conflict: Russia and Ukraine talk about \"coordinated effort\", American analysts consider the US has abandoned the neighbourhood to Russia'', english.hotnews.ro 18 May 2010.]</ref>\n\nIn the early 2010s, experts estimated that Russia is aiming for a \"Taiwanisation\" of Transnistria.<ref>[https://www.osw.waw.pl/en/publikacje/osw-commentary/2012-04-19/russias-strategy-towards-moldova-continuation-or-change Witold Rodkiewicz: ''Russia\u2019s strategy towards Moldova: continuation or change?'', osw.waw.pl/en/ 19 April 2012.]</ref>\n\n==Consular Relations==\nIn 2012, [[Russia]] opened a consulate in Transnistria, despite protests of the government of [[Moldova]].<ref>Helena Ryt\u00f6vuori-Apunen: ''Power and Conflict in Russia\u2019s Borderlands: The Post-Soviet Geopolitics of Dispute Resolution'', London: Bloomsbury Publishing, 2019, p. 122. [https://books.google.de/books?id=uGawDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA122#v=onepage&q&f=false Google Books preview here.]</ref> Nevertheless, Russia has not  recognized Transnistria as an independent state.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Moldova\u2013Russia relations]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Foreign relations of Transnistria}}\n{{Foreign relations of Russia|Europe}}\n\n[[Category:Moldova\u2013Russia relations]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Russia]]\n", "text_old": "Russia\u2013Transnistria relations (Russian: \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e-\u043f\u0440\u0438\u0434\u043d\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043e\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f) is the bilateral relationship between the [[Pridnestrovian Moldovan Republic]] and the [[Russian Federation]]. Russia does not officially recognize the independence of Transnistria. Nevertheless, Russia mantains special relations with Transnistria in the political, military, cultural and economic spheres.\n\n==History==\nThe state of Transnistria was created by local economic elites with special relations to the Soviet and later Russian centre.<ref>Jan Zofka: ''Postsowjetischer Separatismus \u2013 Die pro-russl\u00e4ndischen Bewegungen im moldauischen Dnjestr-Tal und auf der Krim 1989\u20131995'', G\u00f6ttingen: Wallstein Verlag, 2015, passim.</ref>\n\nDuring the reign of [[Igor Smirnov]] (1991\u20132011) mantaining special relations with Russia was a priority of Transnistria.<ref>Marcin Kosienkowski: ''Continuity and Change in Transnistria\u2019s Foreign Policy after the 2011 Presidential Elections'', Lublin: The Catholic University of Lublin Publishing House, 2012, p. 23. [https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/Delivery.cfm/SSRN_ID2183608_code1884160.pdf?abstractid=2143330&mirid=1 Available here.]</ref>\n\nDuring a visit to Kiev in 2010, President [[Dmitri Medvedev]] said he supported a \"special status\" for Transnistria and recognised the \"important and stabilising\" role of the Russian army.<ref>[http://english.hotnews.ro/stiri-regional_europe-7287838-the-transnistrian-conflict-russia-and-ukraine-talk-about-coordinated-effort-american-analysts-consider-the-has-abandoned-the-neighbourhood-russia.htm Anne-Marie Blajan: ''The Transnistrian conflict: Russia and Ukraine talk about \"coordinated effort\", American analysts consider the US has abandoned the neighbourhood to Russia'', english.hotnews.ro 18 May 2010.]</ref>\n\nIn the early 2010s, experts estimated that Russia is aiming for a \"Taiwanisation\" of Transnistria.<ref>[https://www.osw.waw.pl/en/publikacje/osw-commentary/2012-04-19/russias-strategy-towards-moldova-continuation-or-change Witold Rodkiewicz: ''Russia\u2019s strategy towards Moldova: continuation or change?'', osw.waw.pl/en/ 19 April 2012.]</ref>\n\n==Consular Relations==\nIn 2012, [[Russia]] opened a consulate in Transnistria, despite protests of the government of [[Moldova]].<ref>Helena Ryt\u00f6vuori-Apunen: ''Power and Conflict in Russia\u2019s Borderlands: The Post-Soviet Geopolitics of Dispute Resolution'', London: Bloomsbury Publishing, 2019, p. 122. [https://books.google.de/books?id=uGawDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA122#v=onepage&q&f=false Google Books preview here.]</ref> Nevertheless, Russia has not  recognized Transnistria as an independent state.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Moldova\u2013Russia relations]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Foreign relations of Transnistria}}\n{{Foreign relations of Russia|Europe}}\n\n[[Category:Moldova\u2013Russia relations]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Russia]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: mantains \u2192 maintains (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russia%E2%80%93Transnistria_relations"}
{"title_page": "Barnton Quarry", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2017}}\n[[File:DSCN2114 Barnton Quarry Bunker.jpg|thumb|Barnton Quarry and Bunker from Corstorphine Hill]]\n'''Barnton Quarry''' is a disused stone [[quarry]] in [[Corstorphine Hill]], [[Clermiston]], [[Edinburgh]], Scotland. The site was later used as a military command centre, and is now being converted into a museum.\n\nStone was extracted from the quarry until 1914. During the [[Second World War]], the [[Royal Air Force]] (RAF) built a [[RAF Fighter Command|Fighter Command]] operations room in the quarry. In 1952, during the [[Cold War]], this facility was expanded into a central coordination facility for radar stations throughout Scotland. The military authorities closed the site and in 1983 and transferred ownership to the [[Local government in Scotland|local council]].\n\nThe site was subsequently vandalized and damaged by fire. The site is now being cleaned and restored with the goal of creating a local Cold War museum and education centre. The project is being undertaken by volunteers, with funding from the owners of Scotland's Secret Bunker, another disused bunker now run as a tourist attraction.\n\n==History==\n[[File:DSCN2101 Inside Barnton Quarry Bunker.jpg|thumb|Inside Barnton Quarry Bunker during restoration in 2018]]\nBarnton Quarry produced stone until 1914.<ref name=\"EEN 26Feb2013\">{{cite news |url=http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/news/queen-s-edinburgh-nuclear-bunker-to-open-as-museum-1-2810424 |title=Queen\u2019s Edinburgh nuclear bunker to open as museum |first=David |last=O\u2019Leary |work=[[Edinburgh Evening News]] |date=26 February 2013 |accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref> then in 1942 was used as a RAF fighter command operations room.\n\nA bunker was built in 1952<ref name=\"EEN 26Feb2013\"/> as the SOC (Sector Operations Centre) for correlating information from [[ROTOR]] radar stations throughout Scotland. The bunker comprises three underground levels and a large surface building which pre-dates the underground structure.\n\nThe site was re-designated as a [[Regional Seat of Government]] in the early 1960s. The bunker was kept ready to accommodate 400 politicians and civil servants for up to 30 days.<ref name=\"National 18Jan2016\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thenational.scot/news/14901377.Our_Cold_War_secret_bunker_in_an_Edinburgh_suburb/ |title=Our Cold War secret bunker in an Edinburgh suburb |first=Julie |last=McDowall |work=[[The National (Scotland)|The National]] |date=18 January 2016|accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref> It remained operational until the early 1980s. Ownership was transferred to [[Lothian Regional Council]] in 1983.<ref name=\"National 18Jan2016\"/> The Council sold the site in the late 1980s to a private property developer.\n\nThe underground structure was damaged by fire in August 1991 and again in May 1993.<ref name=\"EEN 26Feb2013\"/>\n\nThe site was purchased by James Mitchell, Owner of Scotland's Secret Bunker.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://stv.tv/news/east-central/220026-edinburgh-underground-bunker-to-be-opened-up-to-visitors/ |title=Secret underground bunker in Edinburgh opened up to visitors. The bunker was built beneath Corstorphine Hill during the 1950s to help defend against nuclear war |work=[[STV News]] |date=3 April 2013 |accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref> Since 2011, a team of volunteers has helped with renovation efforts.<ref name=\"National 18Jan2016\"/> The aim is to create a museum and education centre with a view to restoring the [[ROTOR|R4 bunker]] to the original 1952 configuration.<ref name=\"EEN 26Feb2013\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/our-region/edinburgh/corstorphine/inside-the-barnton-quarry-cold-war-nuclear-bunker-1-4082465 |title=Inside the Barnton Quarry Cold War nuclear bunker |work=Edinburgh Evening News |date=25 March 2016 |accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Kelvedon Hatch Secret Nuclear Bunker]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130712161726/http://barntonquarry.org.uk/ Barnton Quarry Restoration Project]\n* [https://secretscotland.wordpress.com/2013/05/11/barnton-quarry-bunker-to-be-developed-as-partner-to-scotlands-secret-bunker-at-anstruther/ Barnton Quarry bunker to be developed as partner to ''Scotland\u2019s Secret Bunker'' at Anstruther. Secret Scotland]\n* [http://www.subbrit.org.uk/rsg/sites/b/barnton_quarry/index.html Barnton Quarry at Subterranea Britannica]\n* [http://www.subbrit.org.uk/rsg/features/sfs/file5.htm Regional Seats of Government article at Subterranea Britannica discussing Barnton Quarry]\n* [http://www.scottish-places.info/features/featurefirst8554.html Barnton Quarry described within the Gazetteer for Scotland of the Royal Scottish Geographic Society]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927191501/http://scotsatwar.co.uk/AZ/barntonpq.htm Barnton Quarry in the Scots at War directory]\n* [http://www.atlasobscura.com/places/barnton-quarry-nuclear-bunker Barnton Quarry Nuclear Bunker at Atlas Obscura] \n* [http://www.abandonedscotland.com/barnton-quarry-rotor-bunker/ Barnton Quarry Rotor Bunker at Abandoned Scotland]\n* [http://www.urbanghostsmedia.com/2015/08/barnton-quarry-abandoned-nuclear-bunker-edinburgh-cold-war/ Barnton Quarry: Cold War Edinburgh\u2019s Abandoned Nuclear Bunker. In Abandoned & Urbex, by Tom Moran, 11 Aug. 2015]\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/cycleologist/sets/72157616429038116/ Barnton Quarry Bunker on Flickr]\n* [http://www.secretbunker.co.uk ''Scotland's Secret Bunker'', Troywood, St. Andrews, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom]\n\n{{coord|55|57|35|N|3|16|40|W|region:GB|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Government buildings completed in 1952]]\n[[Category:Subterranea of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Quarries in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:1952 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Uni