mation from [[ROTOR]] radar stations throughout Scotland. The bunker comprises three underground levels and a large surface building which pre-dates the underground structure.\n\nThe site was re-designated as a [[Regional Seat of Government]] in the early 1960s. The bunker was kept ready to accommodate 400 politicians and civil servants for up to 30 days.<ref name=\"National 18Jan2016\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thenational.scot/news/14901377.Our_Cold_War_secret_bunker_in_an_Edinburgh_suburb/ |title=Our Cold War secret bunker in an Edinburgh suburb |first=Julie |last=McDowall |work=[[The National (Scotland)|The National]] |date=18 January 2016|accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref> It remained operational until the early 1980s. Ownership was transferred to [[Lothian Regional Council]] in 1983.<ref name=\"National 18Jan2016\"/> The Council sold the site in the late 1980s to a private property developer.\n\nThe underground structure was damaged by fire in August 1991 and again in May 1993.<ref name=\"EEN 26Feb2013\"/>\n\nThe site was purchased by James Mitchell, Owner of Scotland's Secret Bunker.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://stv.tv/news/east-central/220026-edinburgh-underground-bunker-to-be-opened-up-to-visitors/ |title=Secret underground bunker in Edinburgh opened up to visitors. The bunker was built beneath Corstorphine Hill during the 1950s to help defend against nuclear war |work=[[STV News]] |date=3 April 2013 |accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref> Since 2011, a team of volunteers has helped with renovation efforts.<ref name=\"National 18Jan2016\"/> The aim is to create a museum and education centre with a view to restoring the [[ROTOR|R4 bunker]] to the original 1952 configuration.<ref name=\"EEN 26Feb2013\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/our-region/edinburgh/corstorphine/inside-the-barnton-quarry-cold-war-nuclear-bunker-1-4082465 |title=Inside the Barnton Quarry Cold War nuclear bunker |work=Edinburgh Evening News |date=25 March 2016